did.unittitle: Papers of Stanley Dance and Helen Oakley Dance
did.abstract: The Papers of Stanley Dance and Helen Oakley Dance are an important resource for the study of 20th-century jazz history in the United States. Of particular interest are transcripts from interviews with a number of jazz musicians, a large selection of photographs, and sound recordings – many of which are unique. Most – but not all – of the material having to do with Earl Hines and Duke Ellington can be found in their respective series. Researchers are advised to examine other series for additional material.

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Materials
separatedmaterial.p: Approximately 50 non-rare commercial videotapes have been separated from the collection.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Stanley Dance (1910-1999) and Helen Oakley Dance (1913-2001) were jazz critics, writers and producers. They married in 1947, having met in New York years earlier, at which time Helen was producing jazz recordings for Irving Mills. Helen Oakley began her career by moving from her native Toronto to Chicago in the early 1930s, where she covered the jazz scene for the fledgling Downbeat magazine. She also founded the Chicago Rhythm Club, which hosted performances by the Benny Goodman Trio and Duke Ellington, among others. Oakley was also producing recordings for various jazz artists, which she continued to do in New York, for Irving Mills. In 1939, she began working for Duke Ellington. During World War II, Helen Oakley joined the Office of Strategic Services and worked in North Africa. After her military service, she moved to England and married Stanley Dance. She spent the next two decades raising a family, before moving to the US and continuing her writing and producing career.

Stanley Dance, born in England, first wrote about jazz in the French journal Jazz hot. After moving to the U.S., he wrote several books and contributed regularly to publications such as Metronome, Saturday Review, and Jazz Journal. Dance conducted interviews with dozens of jazz musicians, and these interviews constitute several of his books and articles. He had a particularly close relationship with Duke Ellington, with whom he prepared Music is My Mistress, Ellington's autobiography.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The arrangement of the Dance Papers relies heavily on the original order of the collection. The Papers are divided into the following series: I. Writings and interviews; II. Files, research materials, programs and posters; III. Clippings; IV. Photographs; V. Correspondence; VI. Materials related to Earl Hines; VII. Materials related to Duke Ellington; and VIII. Sound Recordings.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Materials
relatedmaterial.p: Interviews with Stanley Dance and Helen Oakley Dance can be found in the Duke Ellington Oral History collection, held by Oral History of American Music (OHAM) at Yale University.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Materials
relatedmaterial.p: Interviews with Stanley Dance and Helen Oakley Dance can be found in the Fillius Jazz Archive at Hamilton College.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Papers of Stanley Dance and Helen Oakley Dance are an important resource for the study of 20th-century jazz history in the United States. Of particular interest are transcripts from interviews with a number of jazz musicians, a large selection of photographs, and sound recordings, many of which are unique. Most – but not all – of the material having to do with Earl Hines and Duke Ellington can be found in their respective series. Researchers are advised to examine other series for additional material.

Perhaps the greatest limitation of the Papers is the lack of material from Helen Oakley Dance's career before 1950. This likely has to do with her moves across the Atlantic, and time spent in military service. Researchers are advised to consult the oral history collections listed under Associated Materials.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Writings and Interviews series contains both published and unpublished copies of articles, reviews, columns and liner notes. The vast majority of material was written by Stanley Dance; the small amount of material written by Helen Oakley Dance is labeled as such. There are a number of notebooks and memo books, most of which have identifying titles and/or dates.

As both the Dances' published books rely heavily on oral history, the most significant material in this series can be found in the Interviews and Transcripts sub-series. Many of these interviews are unique, in that they don't appear to have been published or associated with a known oral history collection.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: These newspaper and magazine articles were removed from scrapbooks and photocopied when the collection was initially acquired. There are several article written by Stanley Dance and Helen Oakley Dance, as well as interviews with and articles about the Dances. Also included are interviews with jazz musicians. Publications include Musical Express, The Daily Mirror, Melody Maker, East Anglian Daily Times, The Essex Chronicle, Jazz News and Downbeat. Additional news clippings about Stanley Dance have been added to this box.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The memo books consist of notes taken during live performances, including dates/times, lineups, and tunes played. Also included are quotes, contact information for various people, and miscellaneous notes. Many of the memo books are titled and dated, but some are unlabeled. Most (but not all) appear to be in Stanley Dance's hand.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The interviews included here fall into two general categories: interviews for oral history projects and interviews for future journalistic articles. The oral history project interviews are mostly typed and often do not include the interviewer's questions. Most average approximately 15 to 30 pages in length with some outliers. The article transcripts are generally shorter than the oral history transcripts and are formatted into paragraphs. The articles are occasionally structured as narratives of influential events in the musician's life.

did.unittitle: Stanley Dance & His Olympus Camera Book I

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The first photo album, dated 1968, contains roughly 100 photographs taken by Stanley Dance. Several of the photos contain images of jazz performances from the Newport Jazz Festival and the 1968 Latin American tour. Also included are several offstage shots of jazz players such as Benny Carter, Joe Thomas, Count Basie, Ray Charles, and others.

did.unittitle: Stanley Dance & His Olympus Camera Book II

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The second photo album contains roughly 100 photographs. Included are images from the Latin American tour, 1968, New Orleans, 1969, Newport 1969, New Orleans, 1970, and Earl Hines in San Francisco, 1969. Individuals found in the photos include Duke Ellington, Danny Barker, Tyree Glenn, Buddy Tate, Clark Terry, and others.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains correspondence to and from Stanley and Helen Oakley Dance, with various jazz musicians, friends and family. Note that correspondence with Hugh Panassie and Madeleine Gautier (of the jazz organization Hot Club de France) can be found at the end of the alphabetical listing.

did.unittitle: Correspondence with Madeline Gautier and Hugh Panassié

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Stanley Dance and Helen Oakley Dance collaborated with Earl Hines during the later years of his career. Stanley wrote a book entitled, "The World of Earl Hines", and Helen Oakley Dance ran HiCue records, a publishing company owned by Earl Hines and Johnny Hodges. The majority of material in this series comes from these projects.

did.unittitle: Financial documents and tour related materials

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Contains handwritten financial notes, performance contracts, performance set lists, tour logistical documents, resumes from band musicians, documents from the 1966 tour to Russia, drafts of press releases and articles about Earl Hines, and licensing agreements with several recording and television companies.

did.unittitle: Royalty statements, press quotes, article drafts, and other Hines related materials

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Contains contracts, concert set lists, cancelled checks, royalty statements, press statement quotes,drafts of articles written about Earl Hines, items from the "Hines Manual", photos from "The World of Earl Hines", photoshoot photos, works from the Hi Cue catalogue, and a proposal for an Earl Hines documentary.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Both Stanley Dance and Helen Oakley Dance worked closely with Duke Ellington. This series contains materials indicative of that relationship. Of particular interest is the collection of drafts and notes pertaining to "Music is My Mistress", Ellington's autobiography, which he prepared with Stanley Dance.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Includes typescripts of drafts, interviews, handwritten notes by Duke Ellington and by Stanley Dance. Some material is included in the published version of "Music is My Mistress". There is a substantial amount of material that does not appear in the book, but could have been intended for publication. This includes an interview with Sonny Greer, Q and A sessions (with Duke Ellington), Latin America tour notes from 1968, and various short essays.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series is currently being processed and digitized. It contains several hundred recordings on disc, reel-to-reel tape, and cassette tape. The series includes live shows, radio broadcasts, recording sessions, and a number of dubs. Musicians include Duke Ellington, Earl Hines, Louis Armstrong, Teddy Wilson, Count Basie, and many more.
